<section xml:id="sec-negative-powers-prep" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Negative Powers Prep Activities</title>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-discover-negative-powers">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Let's discover another exponent rule.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use repeated multiplication to rewrite each of the following expressions, then simplify by canceling. Remember, if you cancel everything from the numerator of the fraction, then you're left a <m>1</m> in the numerator.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^2}{x^5}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^3}{x^7}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </task>
    <task>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use the Quotient Rule for Exponents to rewrite each of the following expressions as <m>x^{\text{power}}</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^2}{x^5}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^3}{x^7}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Explain why the last two parts support the reasonableness of the rule <me>\frac{1}{x^n} = x^{-n}</me>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-negative-powers-rewrite">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Let's practice using our new rule, along with other exponent rules, to rewrite expressions.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite as <m>ax^\text{power}</m>: <m>\frac{6}{x}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite as <m>ax^\text{power}</m>:<m>\frac{4x^3}{8x^6}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite without any negative exponents: <m>6^{-1}x^3x^{-5}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rewrite without any negative exponents: <m>\left(4x^{-6}\right)^{-2}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-negative-powers-algebra">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            In many cases, the best way to deal with negative exponents and/or a variable in the denominator in an equation is to move the variable to the other side of the equation using multiplication. For example:
        </p>
        <md>
            <mrow>9 \amp= \frac{5}{x^6}</mrow>
            <mrow>x^6 \cdot 9 \amp= \frac{5}{x^6} \cdot x^6 </mrow>
            <mrow>9x^6 \amp= 5 </mrow>
            <mrow>x^6 \amp= \frac{5}{9} </mrow>
            <mrow>x \amp = \pm \sqrt[6]{\frac{5}{9}} </mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
            Use this strategy to solve each of the equations below.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>\frac{9}{x^{5}} = -3</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>8 = -6x^{-7}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

